04899nam a22006735i 9780824864040DE-B159720210729020517.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210729t20072007hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808248640407 a10.1515/97808248640402doi  a(DE-B1597)483831  a(OCoLC)1024014105  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 4aBL2222.O6592bD43373 2008eb 7aREL0840002bisacsh04a299.5/62221 aStalker, Nancy K., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aProphet Motive :bDeguchi Onisaburō, Oomoto, and the Rise of New Religions in Imperial Japan /cNancy K. Stalker. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2007] 4c©2007  a1 online resource (288 p.) :b29 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgements -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1. Deguchi Onisaburò: Early Life to Oomoto Leadership -- tChapter 2. Neo-Nativism: Oomoto Views on Mythology, Governance, and Agrarianism -- tChapter 3. Taishò Spiritualism -- tChapter 4. Exhibitionist Tendencies: Visual Technologies of Proselytization -- tChapter 5. Paradoxical Internationalism? Oomoto in the World -- tChapter 6. A Patriotic Turn and the Second Suppression -- tConclusion: State, Religion, and Tradition in Imperial Japan -- tNotes -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFrom the 1910s to the mid-1930s, the flamboyant and gifted spiritualist Deguchi Onisaburô (1871–1948) transformed his mother-in-law’s small, rural religious following into a massive movement, eclectic in content and international in scope. Through a potent blend of traditional folk beliefs and practices like divination, exorcism, and millenarianism, an ambitious political agenda, and skillful use of new forms of visual and mass media, he attracted millions to Oomoto, his Shintoist new religion. Despite its condemnation as a heterodox sect by state authorities and the mainstream media, Oomoto quickly became the fastest-growing religion in Japan of the time.In telling the story of Onisaburô and Oomoto, Nancy Stalker not only gives us the first full account in English of the rise of a heterodox movement in imperial Japan, but also provides new perspectives on the importance of "charismatic entrepreneurship" in the success of new religions around the world. She makes the case that these religions often respond to global developments and tensions (imperialism, urbanization, consumerism, the diffusion of mass media) in similar ways. They require entrepreneurial marketing and management skills alongside their spiritual authority if their groups are to survive encroachments by the state and achieve national/international stature. Their drive to realize and extend their religious view of the world ideally stems from a "prophet" rather than "profit" motive, but their activity nevertheless relies on success in the modern capitalist, commercial world.Unlike many studies of Japanese religion during this period, Prophet Motive works to dispel the notion that prewar Shinto was monolithically supportive of state initiatives and ideology.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aReligion and statezJapan. 7aRELIGION / Religion, Politics & State.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUHP eBook Package 2000-2013z978311056414308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Hawaii Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2015z978311066325940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082486404040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780824864040423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780824864040.jpg  a978-3-11-056414-3  UHP eBook Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-066325-9  University of Hawaii Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2015c2000